The problem: Shape-based lossy compression boundary decisions
In computer vision and computational geometry, one of the persistent practical problems is region approximation under area constraint — when you’re simplifying a complex shape (tumor boundary in medical imaging, geographic polygon in GIS, object mask in CV), you need to choose a target representation that minimizes perimeter distortion while preserving area.
Current approaches use iterative algorithms (Ramer-Douglas-Peucker, etc.) that are path-dependent and don’t have clean invariant stopping criteria. You don’t know a priori how much boundary information you’re losing when you move from complex polygon → simplified representation.

